Note:
Runa Standard Library: Numerical Analysis

High-level API for numerical methods that delegates to the high-performance engine.
This provides the user-friendly interface while the engine handles computation.
:End Note

Import "math/core" as Core
Import "math/engine/numerical/core" as NumericalEngine

Note: Root Finding Methods - High-level API
Process called "bisection_method" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number and tolerance as Number returns Number:
    Note: User-friendly bisection method with defaults
    Let max_iterations be 100
    Return NumericalEngine.bisection_engine with f as f and a as a and b as b and tolerance as tolerance and max_iterations as max_iterations

Process called "newton_raphson" that takes f as Process and df as Process and x0 as Number and tolerance as Number returns Number:
    Note: User-friendly Newton-Raphson with defaults
    Let max_iterations be 100
    Return NumericalEngine.newton_raphson_engine with f as f and df as df and x0 as x0 and tolerance as tolerance and max_iterations as max_iterations

Process called "secant_method" that takes f as Process and x0 as Number and x1 as Number and tolerance as Number returns Number:
    Note: User-friendly secant method
    Let max_iterations be 100
    Return NumericalEngine.secant_method_engine with f as f and x0 as x0 and x1 as x1 and tolerance as tolerance and max_iterations as max_iterations

Process called "find_root" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Automatic root finding with best method selection
    Let tolerance be 1e-10
    Return NumericalEngine.brent_method_engine with f as f and a as a and b as b and tolerance as tolerance

Note: Numerical Integration - High-level API
Process called "integrate" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Automatic integration with adaptive quadrature
    Let tolerance be 1e-10
    Return NumericalEngine.adaptive_quadrature_engine with f as f and a as a and b as b and tolerance as tolerance

Process called "trapezoidal_rule" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number and n as Integer returns Number:
    Note: Trapezoidal integration
    Return NumericalEngine.trapezoidal_rule_engine with f as f and a as a and b as b and n as n

Process called "simpson_rule" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number and n as Integer returns Number:
    Note: Simpson's rule integration
    Return NumericalEngine.simpson_rule_engine with f as f and a as a and b as b and n as n

Process called "gaussian_quadrature" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Gaussian quadrature with default 5 points
    Let n be 5
    Return NumericalEngine.gaussian_quadrature_engine with f as f and a as a and b as b and n as n

Note: Numerical Differentiation - High-level API
Process called "derivative" that takes f as Process and x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Automatic numerical differentiation with optimal step size
    Let h be 1e-8
    Return NumericalEngine.central_difference_engine with f as f and x as x and h as h

Process called "forward_difference" that takes f as Process and x as Number and h as Number returns Number:
    Note: Forward difference approximation
    Return NumericalEngine.forward_difference_engine with f as f and x as x and h as h

Process called "backward_difference" that takes f as Process and x as Number and h as Number returns Number:
    Note: Backward difference approximation
    Return NumericalEngine.backward_difference_engine with f as f and x as x and h as h

Process called "central_difference" that takes f as Process and x as Number and h as Number returns Number:
    Note: Central difference approximation
    Return NumericalEngine.central_difference_engine with f as f and x as x and h as h

Process called "high_order_derivative" that takes f as Process and x as Number and order as Integer returns Number:
    Note: High-order derivative using Richardson extrapolation
    Let h be 1e-4
    Return NumericalEngine.richardson_extrapolation_engine with f as f and x as x and h as h and order as order

Note: Interpolation - High-level API
Process called "interpolate" that takes x_data as List[Number] and y_data as List[Number] and x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Automatic interpolation with best method selection
    If x_data.length is less than or equal to 4:
    Return NumericalEngine.polynomial_interpolation_engine with x_data as x_data and y_data as y_data and x as x
    Else:
    Return NumericalEngine.spline_interpolation_engine with x_data as x_data and y_data as y_data and x as x

Process called "linear_interpolate" that takes x_data as List[Number] and y_data as List[Number] and x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Linear interpolation between points
    Return NumericalEngine.linear_interpolation_engine with x_data as x_data and y_data as y_data and x as x

Process called "polynomial_interpolate" that takes x_data as List[Number] and y_data as List[Number] and x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Polynomial interpolation using Lagrange method
    Return NumericalEngine.polynomial_interpolation_engine with x_data as x_data and y_data as y_data and x as x

Process called "spline_interpolate" that takes x_data as List[Number] and y_data as List[Number] and x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Cubic spline interpolation
    Return NumericalEngine.spline_interpolation_engine with x_data as x_data and y_data as y_data and x as x

Note: Convenience functions for common operations
Process called "find_minimum" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Find minimum of function in interval [a, b]
    Let neg_f be lambda x: -(f with x as x)
    Return find_root with f as (lambda x: derivative with f as f and x as x) and a as a and b as b

Process called "find_maximum" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Find maximum of function in interval [a, b]
    Let neg_f be lambda x: -(f with x as x)
    Return find_minimum with f as neg_f and a as a and b as b

Process called "solve_equation" that takes f as Process and initial_guess as Number returns Number:
    Note: Solve equation f(x) = 0 with automatic method selection
    Let df be lambda x: derivative with f as f and x as x
    Return newton_raphson with f as f and df as df and x0 as initial_guess and tolerance as 1e-10